	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I pride myself on having completed a large portion of the quests in EQ (level 33 bard), mostly due to the Charisma Song and a goodly balance of faction plusses gathered from all over, and yet I still have these two staff segments in my bank account for the last 15 levels. I'm stumped as well. I can solo the Bandit now easily, so would be willing to try any ideas out with the segments and keep getting more.<BR>
<BR>
However, given that this seems to be the oldest quest on the books, my gut feeling is that it is an imcomplete quest that differs from all other broken/incomplete quests, in that it gives no indication that it is in fact broken or incomplete.<BR>
<BR>
IMHO, this is EQ's version of &quot;The Missing Link&quot;, and I have a sneaky suspicion they have done nothing about it with the sole purpose of keeping it a deep, dark, unsolved mystery.<BR>
<BR>
One thing I would really, really, really love for them to do though is to confirm that the quest is in fact doable. But, of course, they are not going to do this for two reasons:<BR>
<BR>
  a) If they confirmed it worked, then there would be a sudden surge of people devoting time to solving it, and it would take no time to crack. Most people just give up on it currently.<BR>
<BR>
  b) People who are exploring it are using up a lot of time they would normally be using to level, ultimately shortening their log time with said characters. Something Verant wants to avoid.'<BR>
<BR>
Maybe some guild should offer a prize to the first person that cracks this mystery, either way. Perhaps the added publicity would get more people involved in solving it.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
